{"lemma":"أَوَّلِي","slug":"أَوَّلِي","root":"#.#.ل","root_slug":"_-_-ل","root_link":"/words/roots/_-_-ل","pos":"ADJ","pos_camel":"adj","paradigm":[],"frequency_in_corpus":0,"cross_references":{"qac":{"found":true,"lemma_key":"أَوَّل","root":"أول","pos":"N","occurrence_count":82},"wiktextract":{"found":true,"entry_count":6,"pos_tags":["adj","name","noun","verb"],"has_etymology":true,"sense_count":5},"lanes":{"found":true,"entry_ids":["n1505","n1521","n44747"],"search_url":"https://lanelexicon.com/?s=%D8%A3%D9%8E%D9%88%D9%8E%D9%91%D9%84%D9%90%D9%8A"}},"translations":null,"definition":{"source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"adj","gloss":"first"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"first part, beginning","examples":[{"text":"قَرَأْتُ أَوَّلَ الْكِتَابِ.","english":"I read the beginning of the book."},{"text":"مَا لَهُ أَوَّلٌ وَلَا آخِرٌ.","english":"It has neither a beginning nor an end."}]},{"pos":"name","gloss":"Sunday","tags":["obsolete"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to lead back; to bid to return","tags":["obsolete"]},{"pos":"verb","gloss":"to interpret, to explain"}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"From Proto-Semitic *ʔil-, otherwise أَيْل (ʔayl), إِيل (ʔīl), إِلّ (ʔill), the most important god in the paganic pantheon—equivalent to the Sun, after which in the Western world the Sunday is named, in others. Origin from “first” above is unlikely since all other pagan weekday names are named after planets and thus indirectly gods and the other Semitic languages there employ *ʔaḥad-, which would have been retained. Lastly the Banu Bakr and Taghlib tribes actually worshiped a deity called أَوَال (ʔawāl) or أُوَال (ʔuwāl).\n\nCausative to آلَ (ʔāla, “to return”), semantically like German zurückführen, and paralleling Arabic عَبَّرَ (ʕabbara, “to get across”)."},"ipa":["/ʔaw.wal/"],"lanes_definition":{"source":"lanes","entries":[{"entry_id":"n1505","headword_ar":"اُولَى","root":"Awl","body":[{"kind":"text","text":"fem. of"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^aw~alu","text_ar":"اَ